16:33.118 --> 16:35.537
What room's Erica Wexler in?

16:37.956 --> 16:40.959
Oh, you're not Mr. Jorgensen.
I'm in the wrong room.

16:40.959 --> 16:43.045
- Mr. Gallagher?
- Do I know you?

16:43.045 --> 16:45.171
Oh, you're the woman
who hired my daughter.

16:45.171 --> 16:47.091
- That's right.
- How's she doing?

16:47.091 --> 16:48.633
Oh, Debbie's a gem.

16:48.633 --> 16:50.219
What are you doing back here?

16:50.219 --> 16:52.011
I work here.
I'm a cancer concierge.

16:52.011 --> 16:54.013
A what?

16:54.013 --> 16:56.058
- I--I don't want to keep you.
- No, it's fine.

16:56.058 --> 16:58.435
I'm--I'm waiting for them
to call me for my treatment.

16:58.435 --> 17:00.395
How are you feeling?

17:00.395 --> 17:02.814
Well, I mean, the doctors say
there's always a chance I could

17:02.814 --> 17:06.484
go into remission,
but honestly,

17:06.484 --> 17:09.737
every day I just feel
worse and worse.

17:09.737 --> 17:12.824
I see this all the time
in my business.

17:12.824 --> 17:14.951
The--the hospitals
and the insurance companies

17:14.951 --> 17:17.579
tell you to keep pumping
chemicals into your body

17:17.579 --> 17:22.125
so they can use you as
a bottomless cash machine.

17:22.125 --> 17:24.335
I-if you don't mind my asking,

17:24.335 --> 17:25.462
are your affairs in order?

17:25.462 --> 17:27.213
No.

17:27.213 --> 17:29.340
Because my husband is convinced
I'm gonna get better.

17:29.340 --> 17:30.884
That's why he doesn't come
to the hospital,

17:30.884 --> 17:34.053
because when he comes here,
reality hits.

17:34.053 --> 17:37.265
It's always the spouses
who are in denial.

17:37.265 --> 17:40.268
Thank God, someone who doesn't
think that I'm just gonna be

17:40.268 --> 17:43.146
back on my feet and taking
care of my family.

17:43.146 --> 17:45.440
Sadly, if you don't
take a turn for the better,

17:45.440 --> 17:48.651
it's your husband who will be
left making the arrangements

17:48.651 --> 17:50.737
when he should be grieving.

17:50.737 --> 17:54.240
You know, I'm fully certified
in end-of-life preparations.

17:54.240 --> 17:56.285
I can't afford a specialist.

17:56.285 --> 17:58.162
[laughs]

17:58.162 --> 18:00.330
You think I do this
for the money?

18:00.330 --> 18:02.749
There are a lot of jobs
a Northwestern grad could get

18:02.749 --> 18:05.335
that pay a heck of a lot more
than this.

18:05.335 --> 18:07.003
You went to Northwestern?

18:07.003 --> 18:08.255
Go Wildcats.

18:08.255 --> 18:09.964
I tell you what.

18:09.964 --> 18:12.550
Let's use today
as a trial run.

18:12.550 --> 18:14.178
No charge.

18:14.178 --> 18:15.970
To be totally honest,

18:15.970 --> 18:19.098
I'm happiest when I'm paid
in smiles.

18:19.098 --> 18:21.226
What about your other patient?

18:21.226 --> 18:22.644
He's just a stage two.

18:22.644 --> 18:24.729
Time is a luxury
he still has.

18:24.729 --> 18:27.106
You finish up
what you're doing here,

18:27.106 --> 18:29.317
and I'll take you
to my casket guy.

18:29.317 --> 18:33.238
He'll find you one so comfy,
you'll want stay in it forever.

18:33.238 --> 18:35.740
[laughter]

18:35.740 --> 18:37.242
Ju-- [laughs]

18:37.242 --> 18:40.287
Just a little industry humor.

18:40.287 --> 18:42.664
♪ rock music ♪

18:42.664 --> 18:44.457
You sleep well at night
after a long day

18:44.457 --> 18:46.209
kicking people out
on the street?

18:46.209 --> 18:50.630
♪♪♪

18:50.630 --> 18:52.882
Okay.
Hey.

18:52.882 --> 18:55.134
- Fiona, ugh, finally.
- You call Lip?

18:55.134 --> 18:57.554
Ian and Carl too.
They're on their way.

18:57.554 --> 18:58.930
Thanks, Debs.

18:58.930 --> 19:00.765
I'm still a Gallagher.

19:00.765 --> 19:03.518
Hey, we got permission to stay
in the house until next week.

19:03.518 --> 19:06.271
- From the bank?
- No, the new owners.

19:06.271 --> 19:07.272
Bank owns this place
till the inspection's done.

19:07.272 --> 19:08.273
Bank wants you gone.

19:08.273 --> 19:10.024
Wha--[stammers]

19:10.024 --> 19:11.401
You can't just throw us out
with no warning.

19:11.401 --> 19:13.278
- You get an eviction notice?
- Yeah.

19:13.278 --> 19:18.032
That was your warning.

19:18.032 --> 19:19.325
[Fiona] Motherfucker.

19:19.325 --> 19:21.077
Where are we gonna do
with all this stuff?

19:21.077 --> 19:22.453
This is everything we have.

19:22.453 --> 19:24.248
I'm gonna get some boxes.
Be right back.

19:24.248 --> 19:25.290
What is going on?

19:25.290 --> 19:26.666
We're getting evicted.

19:26.666 --> 19:28.876
This one seems fine.

19:28.876 --> 19:30.795
Absolutely not.

19:30.795 --> 19:32.338
What's wrong with it?

19:32.338 --> 19:35.675
I will not allow you
to be buried in a pine box.

19:35.675 --> 19:37.677
The insects'll be munching
down on you

19:37.677 --> 19:39.178
the second you hit the dirt.

19:39.178 --> 19:40.388
Well, I'm gonna be dead.

19:40.388 --> 19:41.723
I'm not gonna know
the difference.

19:41.723 --> 19:45.101
No, you need stainless steel.

19:45.101 --> 19:47.020
Or mahogany.

19:47.020 --> 19:48.396
Oh, yeah.

19:48.396 --> 19:50.315
Here we go.

19:50.315 --> 19:52.191
The Escalade of coffins.

19:52.191 --> 19:55.820
If you got to go, go in style.

19:55.820 --> 19:57.947
When you're being lowered
into the ground,

19:57.947 --> 20:01.409
you want your loved ones to find
solace in the knowledge that

20:01.409 --> 20:03.369
you're resting comfortably.

20:03.369 --> 20:05.247
- [scoffs]
- [laughs]

20:05.247 --> 20:07.206
It's not for you.
It's for them.

20:07.206 --> 20:08.625
